{"cursor":"17090","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nIn algebra, a 'group ring' is a free module and at the same time a ring,\nconstructed in a natural way from any given ring and any given group. As a free\nmodule, its ring of scalars is the given ring, and its basis is one-to-one with\nthe given group. As a ring, its addition law is that of the free module and its\nmultiplication extends \"by linearity\" the given group law on the basis. Less\nformally, a group ring is a generalization of a given group, by attaching to\neach element of the group a \"weighting factor\" from a given ring.\n\nIf the given ring is commutative, a group ring is also referred to as a group\nalgebra, for it is indeed an algebra over the given ring.\n\nThe apparatus of group rings is especially useful in the theory of group\nrepresentations.\n","linknr":268,"url":"Group_ring","recorded":1362372617,"links":17,"instances":["mathematics","mathematics","mathematics","algebra","mathematics","ring_theory"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Ring theory","Representation theory of groups","Harmonic analysis"],"headings":["Definition","Two simple examples","Some basic properties","Group algebra over a finite group","Group rings over an infinite group","Representations of a group ring","Category theory","Filtration","See also","Notes","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/1/6/016b22c1173624a9004a4af26e2c3925.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/c/c/bccfc7022dfb945174d9bcebad2297bb.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/5/6/0560ef5c046cdbbf197bc7ce4cbfcc4b.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/0/7/007527dc63374769a50d74312434c056.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/3/e/83e05bc10962660378abaf892a9e3180.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/c/3/fc355324d98f795f2f394210316cff77.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/e/c/aeca058d51036487837c12b6ca4d3b8c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/7/5/6756bc055f852502e35732481077e445.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/5/f/15f8e11543cb737d27168a2001